COMPONENT NAME: LKM File to Oracle (SQLLDR)
AUTHOR: Oracle
DESCRIPTION This LKM loads flat file data into Oracle by using the SQL*LOADER utility. Call to SQL*LOADER is made and stdout and stderr are redirected into log files. A specific log file is created by SQL*LOADER. Oracle recommends looking at this file in case of error. Control Files (CTL), Log files (LOG), Discard Files (DSC) and Bad files (BAD) are placed in the work directory defined in the physical schema of the source file.
REQUIREMENTS The source file must be accessible by the ODI agent executing the interface. The agent machine must have Oracle SQL client installed and a valid TNS configuration containing the instance name defined in the Topology. ORACLE_HOME should be set and included in the PATH, so that sqlldr executable can be found. All mappings need to be on the staging area. All source fields need to be mapped for delimited files. Date, Timestamp and Numeric formats should be specified on source columns in the ODI COL_FORMAT field, if they do not match default client NLS settings. Please refer to Java Help for details on format syntax, e.g. "dd-MM-yyyy HH:mm:ss" for Timestamp. Following date and timestamp format translations are supported: Java Oracle Note "y", "Y" // Year, supported: yyyy;yy => 1996;96 "MMMM(M)*" "MONTH" // Month, supported: MMMM => July "MMM" "MON" // Month, supported: MMM => JUL "M" "M" // Month, supported: MM;M => 07;7 "W" "W" // Week in month "w" "WW" // Week in year "DDD" "DDD" // Day in year "dd" "DD" // Day in month "a" "AM" // Am/pm marker "HH" "HH24" // Hour in day (0-23) "KK" "HH12" // Hour in day (0-11) "mm" "MI" // Minute in hour "SSSSSS" "FF6" // Millisecond in second "SSSSS" "FF5" // Millisecond in second "SSSS" "FF4" // Millisecond in second "SSS" "FF3" // Millisecond in second "SS" "FF2" // Millisecond in second "S" "FF1" // Millisecond in second "ss" "SS" // Second in minute "Z" "TZH:TZM" // Timezone, supported: Z => +02:00
BASIC CONFIGURATION 1. Specify the logical format for NUMERIC and DATE columns, if the format does not match client nls settings. 2. Set NLS_DATE_LANGUAGE, if your dates contain language specific elements such as month names and the client language does not match these. Note: select * from nls_session_parameters returns nls settings of client. 3. Set NLS_NUMERIC_CHARACTERS, if your file number format does not match the client NLS settings.
OPTIONS (Refer to Option descriptions for more information on each option) - DELETE_TEMPORARY_OBJECTS: Delete temp objects after integration phase - WORK_TABLE_OPTIONS: table options for work table - LOA_DIRECT: Use direct path insert? - LOA_DISCARDMAX: Max number of records to discard - LOA_ERRORS: Max number of errors for SQL Loader - COMPATIBLE: RDBMS version of staging database - VALIDATE: Validate use of KM and options - NLS_DATE_LANGUAGE: Language of date/timestamp elements - NLS_NUMERIC_CHARACTERS: Override client NLS_NUMERIC_CHARACTERS setting - CHARSET_ENCODING: Character set of the input file
LIMITATIONS Only file technology data types NUMERIC, DATE (including TIMESTAMP) and CHAR are supported. For Timestamps with timezones TZ will be truncated. For loading TS with TZ, please specify the source column as STRING and apply the appropriate String to TS with TZ transformation, e.g. TO_TIMESTAMP_TZ(ALIAS.COL, 'YYYY-MM-DD HH24:MI:SS TZH:TZM') It may occur that SQL*LOADER returns a 0 code (OK) even if the data was not loaded. Consult the log files for more information.
Set this option to NO if you wish to retain temporary objects (files and scripts) after integration. Useful for debugging.

Use this option if you wish to create the work table in nologging mode (transaction is not written to redolog files). This option is set by default to NOLOGGING (valid only from Oracle v8). WARNING : This option should be empty for Oracle v7 configurations

Set this value to TRUE if you wish to use the direct path loading (faster).
Please note that direct path loading is only possible, if NO sql transformations are done on any columns. Whether SQL transformations are reqired depends on KM NLS options and column formats.
Max number of records to discard
Set this property to a greater value if you wish to to discard more than one record.
Max number of errors for SQL Loader
Enter the maximum number of errors allowed in the file.

This option affects the use of PURGE key word and the way statistics are collected:
Values PURGE STATS 10 Yes DBMS_STATS 9 No DBMS_STATS 8 No ANALYZE
Validate use of KM and options

This option generates an extra validation step during development. Validations performed are: - validation of KM option COMPATIBLE - test of mapping location. (Mappings need to be executed on staging)
This option should be turned off for all production use in particular for high-frequency execution. There is not added value in production, only processing overhead.

When loading timestamp data containing language specific elements like the name of a month, this options specifies the language. Valid values are e.g. ENGLISH, FRENCH.
If left blank, the default client setting of executing agent process is used.
Please refer to Oracle Database Globalization Support Guide National Language Support Guide, Appendix A Locale Data, Languages for more details.

When loading numeric values using SQL*Loader, NLS_NUMERIC_CHARACTERS setting of client defines decimal separator, if this option is left blank.
Otherwise NLS_NUMERIC_CHARACTERS defined here are used for loading numeric values. The option is a two-character string. The first character defines the decimal separator and the second character defines the grouping character.
Note: Setting NLS_NUMERIC_CHARACTERS to anything else then the default, will result in appropriate SQL expressions in the SQL*Loader script preventing direct path loading. Therefore NLS_NUMERIC_CHARACTERS cannot be used with LOA_DIRECT=YES. This is not supported by SQL*Loader. Please consider LKM File to Oracle (External Table) in such sitatuations.
Character set encoding for SQLLDR control file.
Character set encoding for load data file. E.g. UTF8.

package com.oracle.odi.km.ext;

public class FormatTranslator {
	// Java Date Formatting information available at http://java.sun.com/j2se/1.4.2/docs/api/java/text/SimpleDateFormat.html
	// Oracle Date Formatting information available in Oracle SQL Language Reference: Chapter "Basic Elements fo Oracle SQL": DateTime Format Elements
	
	static String[][] transTableDate = {
	    {"y",		"Y"},	// Year, supported:  yyyy;yy => 1996;96
	    {"MMMM(M)*",	"month"},	// Month, supported: MMMM => July
	    {"MMM",		"mon"},	// Month, supported: MMM => JUL
	    {"M",		"M"},	// Month, supported: MM;M => 07;7
	    {"month",		"MONTH"},	// (auxiliary)
	    {"mon",		"MON"},	// (auxiliary)
	    {"W",		"W"},	// Week in month
	    {"w",		"WW"},	// Week in year 
	    {"DDD",		"DDD"},	// Day in year 
	    {"dd",		"DD"},	// Day in month
	    {"a",		"AM"},	// Am/pm marker 
	    {"HH",		"HH24"},	// Hour in day (0-23)
	    {"KK",		"HH12"},	// Hour in day (0-11)
	    {"mm",		"MI"},	// Minute in hour 
	    {"SSSSSS",	"FF6"},	// Millisecond in second 
	    {"SSSSS",		"FF5"},	// Millisecond in second 
	    {"SSSS",		"FF4"},	// Millisecond in second 
	    {"SSS",		"FF3"},	// Millisecond in second 
	    {"SS",		"FF2"},	// Millisecond in second 
	    {"S",		"FF1"},	// Millisecond in second 
	    {"ss",		"SS"},	// Second in minute 
	    {"Z",		"TZH:TZM"}	// Timezone, supported: Z => +02:00
	};	   

	public static String translate( String srcDT, String colFormat ) throws Exception {
		String format = "";
		
		if (colFormat.trim().length()==0) 
			/* we use Oracle's default format */
			format = "";
		else {
			// Is source column a date?
			if ( srcDT.toUpperCase().equals( "DATE") ) {
				format = colFormat;
				for (int i = 0; i < transTableDate.length; i++)
					format = format.replaceAll( transTableDate[i][0], transTableDate[i][1] );
			} else 
			// Is source column a numeric?
			if ( srcDT.toUpperCase().equals( "NUMERIC")) {
				format = "";
			} else 
			// Is source column anything else than a string?
			if ( !srcDT.toUpperCase().equals( "STRING" )) 
				throw new OdiKMException("ODIKM-FILE-10007", "ODIKM-FILE-10007: No format translation defined for data type {0}", new Object[] {srcDT} );
		};
		if ( format.length() > 0 )
			format = format;
		return format;
	}

}

public class sqlldrColFormat {
	public static String	nlsDateLanguage = "<%= (odiRef.getOption("NLS_DATE_LANGUAGE").length()==0)?"":"NLS_DATE_LANGUAGE=''"+odiRef.getOption("NLS_DATE_LANGUAGE")+"''"%>"; 
	public static boolean	enforceNlsNumChars = <%=(odiRef.getOption("NLS_NUMERIC_CHARACTERS").length()>0)?"true":"false"%>; 
	public static String	nlsNumChars = "NLS_NUMERIC_CHARACTERS=''<%=odiRef.getOption("NLS_NUMERIC_CHARACTERS")%>''";

	public static String get( String colName, srcDataType, destDataType, colFormat, colPrecision, colScale, colBytes ) {
		String format = "";
		String oracleDataFormat = FormatTranslator.translate( srcDataType, colFormat );

		// Is the source column a DATE?
		if ("DATE".equals(srcDataType)) { 
			dataType = "";
			dataConvFunc = "";
			// How many digits are there for milliseconds?
			int precision = colFormat.replaceAll("[^S]","").length();
			// Does the source column contain a timezone?
			if (colFormat.indexOf("Z")>-1) {
				if (precision > 0) {
					dataType = "TIMESTAMP(" + precision.toString() + ") WITH TIME ZONE";
				} else {
					dataType = "TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE";
				};
				dataConvFunc = "TO_TIMESTAMP_TZ";
			// Does the source column contain milliseconds?
			} else if (precision > 0) {
				dataType = "TIMESTAMP(" + precision.toString() + ")"; 
				dataConvFunc = "TO_TIMESTAMP"; 
			} else {
				dataType = "DATE";
				dataConvFunc = "TO_DATE";
			};
			// Does the source column contain a language specifc element and has a date language been specified?
			if ((colFormat.indexOf("MMM")>-1 ||
			    colFormat.indexOf("a")>-1) &&
			    nlsDateLanguage.length()>0) {
				// Explicit conversion function required
				format = " "+(char)34+dataConvFunc+"(:"+colName+", '"+oracleDataFormat+"', '"+nlsDateLanguage+"')"+(char)34;
			} else {
				// Is there a column format defined for this column?
				if (colFormat.length()>0) {
					// Implicit conversion by date_format clause
					format = " "+dataType+" "+(char)34+oracleDataFormat+(char)34;
				} else {
					// Use client nls settings to convert date/timestamp
					format = "";
				};
			};
		} else

		// Is the source column a NUMERIC?
		if ("NUMERIC".equals(srcDataType)) {
			// Do we need to enforce NLS settings for numbers?
			if (enforceNlsNumChars) {
				if (colPrecision.length() == 0)
					throw new OdiKMException("ODIKM-FILE-10011", "ODIKM-FILE-10011: Column {0}: Precision is not defined! Please correct precision", new Object[] {colName} );
				if (colScale.length() == 0)
					throw new OdiKMException("ODIKM-FILE-10012", "ODIKM-FILE-10012: Column {0}: Scale is not defined! Please correct scale", new Object[] {colName} );
				precision = new Integer(colPrecision).intValue();
				scale = new Integer(colScale).intValue();
				// Build a number format according to precision and scale
				digitsInFront = precision - ((scale==0)?0:(scale + 1));
				digitsBehind = scale;
				if (digitsInFront < 0)
					throw new OdiKMException("ODIKM-FILE-10010", "ODIKM-FILE-10010: Column {0}: Scale > Precision is not supported. Please correct precision/scale", new Object[] {colName} );
				format = " "+(char)34+"TO_NUMBER(:"+colName+", '";
				format += "99999999999999999999999999999999999999".substring(0,digitsInFront);
				if (digitsBehind>0) {
					format += "D";
					format += "99999999999999999999999999999999999999".substring(0,digitsBehind);
				};
				format += "', '"+nlsNumChars+"')"+(char)34;
			} else {
				format = "DECIMAL EXTERNAL";
			};
		} else {

		// The source column is a STRING => add char(length) for length greater than 255
			if (colBytes.length() == 0)
				throw new OdiKMException("ODIKM-FILE-10013", "ODIKM-FILE-10013: Column {0}: Physical length is not defined! Please correct length", new Object[] {colName} );
			taille = new Integer(colBytes).intValue(); 
			if (taille > 254) 
			format = "CHAR("+colBytes+")";
			else 
			format ="";
		};

		return format;
	}
}

public static String stringToHex(String base)
    {
     StringBuffer buffer = new StringBuffer();
     int intValue;
     for(int x = 0; x < base.length(); x++)
         {
    	 
         intValue = base.charAt(x);
         buffer.append(Integer.toHexString(intValue));
     }
     return buffer.toString();
}

COMPONENT NAME: LKM File to SQL
AUTHOR: Oracle
Description: - Loading Knowledge Module - Loads data from an ASCII or EBCDIC File to any ISO-92 compliant database. - This module uses ODI Agent to read selected data from the source file and write the result in the target temporary table created dynamically.
Restrictions: - Source file must be physically accessible by ODI Agent. - All mappings must be executed on staging or target. - This Knowledge Module is NOT RECOMMENDED when using LARGE VOLUMES. Other specific modules using Bulk utilities (SQL*LOADER, BULK INSERT etc) are usually more efficient.
Set this option to NO if you wish to retain temporary objects (tables, files and scripts) after integration. Useful for debugging.
IKM Oracle Slowly Changing Dimension RPA

COMPONENT NAME: IKM Oracle Slowly Changing Dimension RPA AUTHOR: Stewart Bryson, Red Pill Analytics DESCRIPTION - Set-based SCD Type 1 and Type 2 handling user SQL analytics instead of numerous tables and statements - Data can be controlled. Invalid data is isolated in the Error Table and can be recycled. REQUIREMENTS When defining a dimension table in the Model, it's required to configure the following options in the Slowly Changing Dimension Behavior screen: Surrogate Key: A single column mapped to a sequence value. Natural Key: A column or columns representing the Natural Key or Business Key for the entity in the source. Overwrite Column: Designates a column as a Type 1 SCD Insert Row: Designates a column as a Type 2 SCD Current Record Flag: A single column indicating that a dimensional record is the most recent Start Timestamp: A Date Column representing the Effective Date End Timestamp: A Date Column representing the Expiration Date
Commit all data inserted or updated in the target datastore.
Check this option if you wish to perform flow control.
Check this option to recycle data rejected by flow control in a previous execution of this interface.
Check this option to control the target table after having inserted or updated target data.
Check this option if you wish to truncate the target datastore.
Check this option if you wish to delete all the rows of the target datastore.
Check this option if you wish to create the target table

This option affects the use of PURGE key word and the way statistics are collected: Values PURGE STATS 10 Yes DBMS_STATS 9 No DBMS_STATS 8 No ANALYZE

This option generates an extra validation step during development. COMPONENT NAME: LKM File to Oracle (EXTERNAL TABLE)
AUTHOR: Oracle
DESCRIPTION This LKM loads flat file data into Oracle by using Oracle external tables. Depending on column data types, data formats and KM options chosen, the KM may need to create a view on top of the external table to perform format conversions e.g. for dates.
This LKM supports multiple worker processes to load data from multiple files in parallel. Multiple files separated by comma can be specified in the "Resource Name" field of the data store. - INVENTORY1.DAT, INVENTORY2.DAT, INVENTORY3.DAT With ORACLE_LOADER access driver, wild-cards asterisk (*) and question (?) can be used in the file names. - INVEN*.DAT - INVENTORY?.DAT ORACLE_DATAPUMP access driver does not support wild-cards.
REQUIREMENTS Source file must be accessible by Oracle instance. All mappings need to be executed on staging. For delimited files, all source fields need to be mapped. Date and Timestamp formats should be specified on source columns in the ODI COL_FORMAT field, if they do not match default database NLS settings. Please refer to Java Help for details on format syntax, e.g. "dd-MM-yyyy HH:mm:ss" for Timestamp. Following date and timestamp format translations are supported: Java Oracle Note "y", "Y" // Year, supported: yyyy;yy => 1996;96 "MMMM(M)*" "MONTH" // Month, supported: MMMM => July "MMM" "MON" // Month, supported: MMM => JUL "M" "M" // Month, supported: MM;M => 07;7 "W" "W" // Week in month "w" "WW" // Week in year "DDD" "DDD" // Day in year "dd" "DD" // Day in month "a" "AM" // Am/pm marker "HH" "HH24" // Hour in day (0-23) "KK" "HH12" // Hour in day (0-11) "mm" "MI" // Minute in hour "SSSSSS" "FF6" // Millisecond in second "SSSSS" "FF5" // Millisecond in second "SSSS" "FF4" // Millisecond in second "SSS" "FF3" // Millisecond in second "SS" "FF2" // Millisecond in second "S" "FF1" // Millisecond in second "ss" "SS" // Second in minute "Z" "TZH:TZM" // Timezone, supported: Z => +02:00
BASIC CONFIGURATION 1. Specify the logical format for NUMERIC and DATE columns, if the format does not match database nls settings. 2. Set NLS_DATE_LANGUAGE, if your dates contain language specific elements such as month names and the database language does not match these. Note: select * from nls_database_parameters returns nls settings of database. 3. Set NLS_NUMERIC_CHARACTERS, if your file number format does not match the database default settings.
OPTIONS (Refer to Option descriptions for more information on each option) - DELETE_TEMPORARY_OBJECTS: Delete temp objects after integration phase - EXT_MISSING_FIELD: Empty Fields are set to NULL - EXT_CHARACTERSET: Character set used for loading - EXT_STRING_SIZE: Length for character strings in byte - EXT_REJECT_LIMIT: Max number of errors for Loader - EXT_PARALLEL: Load using the parallel option - VALIDATE: Validate use of the KM - NLS_DATE_LANGUAGE: Language of date/timestamp elements - NLS_NUMERIC_CHARACTERS: Override database NLS_NUMERIC_CHARACTERS setting - EXT_ACCESS_DRIVER: Access driver to be used to load data into oracle. Supportd access drivers are - ORACLE_LOADER - ORACLE_DATAPUMP - EXT_PARALLEL_LOADERS: Number of worker processes to be employed to load data in parallel
LIMITATIONS Only file technology data types NUMERIC, DATE (including TIMESTAMP) and CHAR are supported. For Timestamps with time zones TZ will be truncated. For loading TS with TZ, please specify source column as STRING and apply the appropriate String to TS with TZ transformation, e.g. TO_TIMESTAMP_TZ(ALIAS.COL, 'YYYY-MM-DD HH24:MI:SS TZH:TZM')
Set this option to NO to retain temporary objects (files and scripts) after integration. Useful for debugging.
Empty Fields are set to NULL
'Missing field values are null' indicates that fields are set to NULL, if fields have not been filled with values.
Load using the character set option. Examples: CHARACTERSET 'WE8ISO8859P1' CHARACTERSET 'WE8EBCDIC500'
Length for character strings in byt

The STRING SIZES ARE IN clause is used to indicate whether the lengths specified for character strings are in bytes or characters. Examples:: STRING SIZES ARE IN CHARACTERS STRING SIZES ARE IN 2 BYTES
Max number of errors for Loader
Enter the maximum number of errors allowed in the file. Examples: UNLIMITED to except all errors. Integer value (10 to allow 10 rejections)
Set this value to PARALLEL to use the Oracle parallel load (faster).

This option generates an extra validation step during development. Validations performed are: - Test of mapping location. (Mappings need to be executed on staging)
This option should be turned off for all production use in particular for high-frequency execution. There is not added value in production, only processing overhead.

When loading timestamp data containing language specific elements such as the name of a month, this options specifies the language. Valid values are e.g. ENGLISH, FRENCH.
If left blank, the default client setting of executing agent process is used.
Please refer to Oracle Database Globalization Support Guide National Language Support Guide, Appendix A Locale Data, Languages for more details.

If set to blank, NLS_NUMERIC_CHARACTERS setting of database defines decimal separator for loading numeric values using external tables.
Otherwise the NLS_NUMERIC_CHARACTERS defined here are used for loading numeric values. This option is a two-character string. The first character defines the decimal separator and the second character defines the grouping character.
Note: Setting NLS_NUMERIC_CHARACTERS to anything else then the default, results in an additional view layer with appropriate SQL expressions.
